"{\"uid\": \"cbc.ca-news-canada-manitoba-paris-olympics-triathlete-tyler-mislawchuk-1.7281092\", \"text\": \"A Manitoba Olympian hopes his performance at the 2024 Paris\\u00a0Olympic Games will inspire young athletes in the province and across the country.  On Wednesday, Tyler Mislawchuk\\u00a0of Oak Bluff, a small community just southwest of Winnipeg,\\u00a0becamethe first Canadian Olympian to finish in the Top 10 of the men's triathlon since 2008, when Simon Whitfield won silver in Beijing.  The 29-year-old secured a ninth-place result in the event, after finishing 15th at both the 2016 Rio Olympic Games and the 2020 Tokyo Games.  \\\"I am from Oak Bluff, Manitoba.\\u00a0It's -55 in the winter - school closed,\\u00a0[you] climb through snow banks to get to school,\\\" he told CBC Sports\\u00a0after the event, which features a\\u00a01.5-kilometre\\u00a0swim, a 40-kilometre bike ride and a 10-kilometre run.  \\\"I am here at the Summer Olympics, the biggest sporting stage in the world, and \\u2026 I started at [the]Manitoba Games.\\u00a0I did not even get on the podium at Manitoba Games, and I [fought] for a medal at the Olympics.  \\\"No matter where you are at your level \\u2026 do not give up. Keep fighting.\\\"  \\\"Keep fighting\\\" \\ud83d\\ude24<br><br>Tyler Mislawchuk hopes to inspire Canadians after his incredible top 10 triathlon finish at <a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/Paris2024?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\\\">#Paris2024</a><br><br>More: <a href=\\\"https://t.co/EZLPmMGGpC\\\">https://t.co/EZLPmMGGpC</a> <a href=\\\"https://t.co/FrHo7vdgDD\\\">pic.twitter.com/FrHo7vdgDD</a>  Mislawchukposted on Instagramprior to the Olympics that he hoped the third time would be the charm, after his previous appearances at the Olympic Games in\\u00a0Tokyo,\\u00a0where his hopes for a podium finish were dashed when he was injured during the race, and in Rio.  \\\"I am proud of the effort,\\\" he said.  Mislawchuk has had supporters back home cheering him on.  Members of the province's triathlon community gathered along a service road in Oak Bluff, where Mislawchuk trained, on Monday, when the triathlon event was originally scheduled to take place. Itwas postponedto Wednesday over concerns about water quality in the Seine River, where the swimming portion of the race took place.  \\\"We are so lucky with Tyler as an ambassador for our sport and \\u2026 for our province,\\\" Triathlon Manitoba executive director Jared Spier said on Monday.  \\\"He's exactly who you want to cheer for. He's hard-working, he's well-spoken. He's got no ego about him.\\u2026 It's great to have everybody behind him, because it's so easy to get behind him.\\\"  Meanwhile, Mislawchuk\\u00a0- who said he\\u00a0always races until \\\"the wheels come off\\\"\\u00a0-\\u00a0said he's grateful for the people who never stopped believing in him along the way, and hopes it may help inspire others.  \\\"If some kid in Oak Bluff,\\u00a0Man., or Quebec\\u00a0or B.C. can take a little bit of inspiration of how I fought out there, then job done.\\\"  With files from CBC Sports and Cameron MacLean  Audience Relations, CBCP.O. Box 500 Station AToronto, ONCanada, M5W 1E6  Toll-free (Canada only):1-866-306-4636  It is a priority for CBC to create products that are accessible to all in Canada including people with visual, hearing, motor and cognitive challenges.  Closed Captioning and Described Video is available for many CBC shows offered onCBC Gem.  \"}"